Notes: Last day w/ Susan and link. Great climb. Led P4. Would love to return and led them all. P2 was little complicated. Take your time and find good holds, jams, and feet (behind you). P3 was spooky and delicate but would lead. Take time on traverse. Link built trad anchor top P5, so Susan and I got a free mini lead pitch on the crux moves to get to the rap rings.
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (10) Pine Creek Canyon > Brass Wall

Notes:
W/ Jack, link, and Elizabeth. Lead P1, 34, 89 
Jack linked P5-7 required with 70 and 5m of simuling. P1 was awesome, runout was fine. Absurd beta from me on p3. RH ring lock, LH sloper, RF foot jam, LF smear. I definitely don’t over climb 5.6. Great day.
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (12) Oak Creek Canyon > Solar Slab - Upper Tier

Notes: Followed/ Jack. W/ link and Elizabeth. Jack linked 1,2,3 with a 70m plus 5-10m of simuling. Rapped twice with two 70s
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (12) Oak Creek Canyon > Solar Slab - Lower Tier

Notes:
W/ Jack and Susan. We crushed. Led P1. 
P1 was slabby, felt sketch. 
Jack led p2-4, p2 5.6 but awkward, slick, and committing; would lead but would be stressful. P3, fell off lay back 10-15" up forward. Was spooky because it was a true fall. But bad beta, need to find handjams deep in the crack and use feet inside crack instead of layback. Rest of climbing was sweet. P4 off width was fine but would be scary lead. Use small holds inside crack and reach high. 2 raps with twins. Maybe full thing, next trip?
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (10) Pine Creek Canyon > Mescalito > Dark Shadows Wall

Notes:
W/ Tom behind Susan and Jack. Led P1/3/5
P1 a bit sketch but manageable, forgot the nuts wish I had them. Committing move out left. Apparently placed a .3 as a nut and then forgot to clip it or it unclipped itself?? P3 chill, P5 traverse used good holds as feet and worked over. Scary ass chimney. Had to hang bag, and Jack left a 3 for me which helped, still one of the more bold leads I’ve had. Also pulled up rope  too much and almost pulled Tom off the cliff. Descent through gully on right
Anchors: 
P1: 1,2,3
P2: 0.75, 0.5, yellow and blue totem. 4 would have been nice
P3: 0.75, 2, 3
P4: 0.2, 0.3, little blue nut, slung chicken head on left
P5: 0.5, 0.4, blue or black totem
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (11) Juniper Canyon > Rose Tower

Notes: W/ Susan. Led P2, Cheated 2nd Clip, stay further right
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (05) Sandstone Quarry > Parking Lot Area > Man's Best Friend Area

Notes: W/ Susan. Led P1, fun and chill, easy approach. Rapped in, Scrambled Gully to exit
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (05) Sandstone Quarry > Parking Lot Area > Man's Best Friend Area

Notes: W/ Filipe, we did 5.6 variation of the next, he lead P1 i lead P23. I would stick to normal route for when I lead it. P23 was harder than anticipated, the traverse has very poor hands but good feet if you stretch it out
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > c. Frog's Head - the Arch

Notes: W/ Felipe. I lead 1/3 he lead 2. Mine were fine and fun but no notes. The traverse pitch was awesome. 120 cm on second peace in first corner. Some froggy stance move which will be spooky on lead but seriously cool. Crux is chalked jugs with piton. Then cut feet and have fun.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > f. The Guides' Wall (Madame G's)

Notes: Split leads with Felipe. He crushed, i didn’t look at guide book and definitely did a variation on P1. Would love to come back and lead the whole thing. Crux is actually first lil dihedral on p2 where you have to smear foot on arete. It’s good just go for it. Second crux is standing Waco. Just over crimp and get your weight under your feet. Last crux is the last mantle. Go right more than you think. Last good peice is pro is the #3 on the last roof pull
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > f. The Guides' Wall (Madame G's)

Notes: With Holly, very polished and didn't love the gear got to the overhang move and didn't trust the gear or feet so downclimbed
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > r. Far Face

Notes: W/ Holly. strugged on P2 didn't get this time
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > i. Orangutan Buttress

Notes: W/ Holly, fun, not sure why we don't do this everytime we set open face slab
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > h. Open Face

Notes: W/ Holly
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > h. Open Face

Notes: W/ Mike. Always fun, mike ended up facing outwards in the chimney?!  We should do it again next time and tick the footholds or do face variation
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Mike. Open on a fall saturday?! Mike's first trad climb and multipitch! He absolutely crushed and the climb was more exposed then I remember it being two weeks ago. He locked in, and face climbed super confidently although I don't think he looked down once. Super proud of him, Incredible family experience
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > f. The Guides' Wall (Madame G's)

Notes: W/ mike, he belayed. First 20 ft was stiff, two good hands and then a half pad three finger side pull on a 5.4/5,5???? still great and fun moves but one or two unexpected harder moves off the deck. After second undercling roof there was a 20 ft run out which I couldn't solve but I just went for it. Climbed with a 60m and the unweighted rope ends barely reached the ground. No problem will weighted.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > a1. The Uberfall - left

Notes: With Seb, never has this climb felt smoother. Great lead day, maybe a little stronger and alot more confidence made this a really fun and enjoyable pitch. No stress.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Seb. Did it in one pitch. Very fast maybe half hour to get us both up. So fun
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Seb. Did it in one pitch. Beginning is still burly. I didn't hesitate at all on the move but I didn't plan the feet after I hit the move. Next time, look down before making the move, would be less stressful. Maybe the first time I actually finished the last 20 ft appropriately and didn’t end up on belly roll
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Seb. Linked P1 and p2. Rope drag was okay. Last piece before the traverse was dumb. P3 was a bit intimidating to get out but so good once I committed. Rest of face was beautiful. Took it slow didn’t get pumped. This was a goal for the fall, so really happy. Maria/Madam G next.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > i. High E

Notes: With Holly. I led p1. She led the money p2 and crushed it. Second trad lead for her and really great placements. Finished in the dark
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Holly. Really fun p2 and good p3. Fun dihedral moves. Not my best anchor on top of p2 but gotta do what you gotta do
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > f. The Guides' Wall (Madame G's)

Notes: With Holly. Fun and easy climb. Some enjoyable placements. Met good people, Joe and Heather. Rapped early to avoid congo-line on beginners rappel.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > f. The Guides' Wall (Madame G's)

Notes: With Link. Oak and Annie on March of Dimes. P1 led was fun but a bit heady at times. No pro for first 20 ft of a traverse on small hands and feet with a karate kick finish. Very satisfying, then some dihedreal climbing with small R feet into an overhang. Some sections really had little pro and small crack hands, where pulling on a couple fingers was the best you got. Great belay from L who was talking to O on the radio the whole time haha. L lead P23, which had 15 ft of burly climbing on a good hand crack but honestly felt a bit sweaty this day. Link went onto finish on Wind Ridge P4 but I failed crux move twice off the deck and ran out of time. I walked off / L rapp. L, O, A, and I celebrated with margs. Perfect weekend
Location: Colorado > Boulder > Eldorado Canyon State Park > The Wind Tower > Wind Tower - SW Face

Notes: W/ Link. Amazing experience, best lead so far.  Link placed first piece to protect glassy foot. Was unnecessary looking back but a really good confidence boost and it was nice to know I wasn't going to deck. The rest of the climb doesn't have anything as glassy as that first foot transitioning from R to L flake. I linked P1/2; I took it really slow but it was very enjoyable and challenging. I did not stem the right and left flake but jammed the RF and had the LF on the face. I would have appreciated having my large set of nuts, the anchor at the top of P2 took .5-1 cams. Link lead P34, I think P3 was as challenging as P1 and would have required some effort but P4 was chill and would love to lead that next time. I led P5 and built an anchor on top out of . 4-.75 size. Very fun and grateful to link for encouragement. Was definitely an experience to remember.
Location: Colorado > Boulder > Eldorado Canyon State Park > The Bastille > The Bastille - N Face

Notes: W/ Oak. Annie and Link climbed super slab / EL 100 nearby. First approach ramp was fine but honestly fatigue in calves made it a bit scary. Oak and I started same time, he tagged the line and I tied in once he made to top, to speed up the process. First three moves of P1 might have been crux, less than ideal finger crack to a jug. Also found the layback crack hard, took at the top. Feet are smears most of the time. Loved P3 traverse with the downclimb to the jug and then the step through. Down climbed to second half on belay but was okay. Linked P4/5 in a really enjoyable dihedral. P6 was rotten band, be careful with choss. Some burly but really fun climbing into face climbing with few holds but big feet. Descent:  hiked to join L/A for some fun rappels. Finished about 5/10 mins ahead of them. ty Oak!
Location: Colorado > Boulder > Eldorado Canyon State Park > Redgarden Wall > Redgarden - Tower One

Notes: W/ Link. Really amazing climb as a follower but looked really difficult to protect as a leader. L said 2 stars due to pro, i though follower moves were 3.5 stars. Loved the footwork. Linked P2/3/4 Regardless If I end back on rewritten it's more fun to do P1 of Zot. Rapped off tat on top of p4 to do Rewr. When pulling rope, falling rock almost broke L's foot.
Location: Colorado > Boulder > Eldorado Canyon State Park > Redgarden Wall > Redgarden - Lumpe to the top

Notes: W/ Link. Climbed Great Zot then rapped off of P4 onto P1 of Rewritten. P2 unprotected ramp to eye bolt. Linked P3/4 which is a bit crazy, since it include the traverse. I though moves were amazing but would be a heady lead on the traverse especially. Traverse looked sketch but as soon as you commit the feet appear out of nowhere and the hands are bomber. Finished on the arete which was amazing. Descent: Hiked off life followed cairns, pretty straightforward. faster than the optional rapp
Location: Colorado > Boulder > Eldorado Canyon State Park > Redgarden Wall > Redgarden - Lumpe to the top

Notes: W/ Link. So good. Pretty tough to protect but was great and well worth the time. Also, move back to head wall at the back of the arete was an unexpected extra bonus
Location: Colorado > Boulder > Eldorado Canyon State Park > Redgarden Wall > Redgarden - Lumpe to the top

Notes: With Sara and Lucia. As great of a climb as I remembered. First roof pull was probably crux. Ended up using small RF under the roof to wedge myself inside in order to place gear and rest but didn’t love how small and polished that RF was. Felt great to get through. The roof was also really fun, placed #3 right before then checked out holds before resting and then going for it. One of my best lead trad experiences so far. Sara and Lucia both crushed the pitch and enjoyed the challenge of the roof. Sara expertly deployed some beach whaling techniques that I think she learned from me. We went on for p2 even though the sun was setting and we had one headlamp between the three of us but it’s too nice of a pitch to skip. Got down safe in the dark for Sara’s last climb as a Princetonian. Beta: work fast through an intermediate jug or two on the roof. Large circular horizontal flake at center top of roof is bomber.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Sara and Lucia. I found the first 20ft pretty committing but got through. Definitely didn’t feel 100%. Sara and Lucia said they got through just fine. Corner was still pretty stressful and but got up it slowly. Traverse felt fun and easy. Sara didn’t like the traverse much because of rope twisting plus exposure. I had to build hanging trad anchor and pitch it out because of rope drag but with one follower. Doing it in one pitch would be doable, more fun, and much more time efficient. P2 is still fun but easier. Rappelled down easily with two 60s. Maybe in one 70, would have to check
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > a1. The Uberfall - left

Notes: W/ Sara and Lucia. Returning to my first gunks follow four years later. I did not remember anything tbh. Really fun climbing all the way through. We got on behind a fun group. P1 was nice short and nice traversing. P2 had a rock over move which I was a bit nervous for, barely any hands and little to no good gear. I fit a shitty .2 and a nut, not sure either would have held. It’s really a nothing move but felt heady. I got one of the two ropes really stuck in a crack rounding that corner. Be more careful next time. P3 was the best 5.4 I’ve experience felt exposed but perfect holds. Heady but really enjoyable. Hiked off. Sara and Lucia were a bit bored waiting but ultimately really enjoyed the climbing
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Near Trapps > a. Beginning of cliff to Gelsa

Notes: With Lucia, Followed by Cyrill and Seb! Lucia and Seb’s first multipitch and trad climb. Linked P1 and P2. Will do this from now on. Barely any rope drag. Ended up behind a slow but very friendly party. Still love keep hands low on P3 and walking feet. Felt even easier this time and still as much fun. We had some troubles with the double rope rappel with 9.8mm due to Seb and Lucia not weighing enough plus it being their first time. Note: two 70m reached the ground. Solution: tie off one side of the rap with an eight knot and send them down on a single strand. Last person with enough weight and experience unties knots and raps on both. Rappel took so long that Cyrill got too bored and solo’d back up the route to rappel with us again
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > e. The Mac Wall (Something Interesting)

Notes: With Lucia. Tied together P1 and P2 which was a much more fun way of climbing this. I’ll do it in one pitch from now on if free. Cyrill had all my 120s so I had a difficult time manage slack but still quite easy! 1:20 ground to ground. Took a bit of time to find a dropped nut but we found it!
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Lucia. Start is a bit committing but you’re going dynamically to good holds. I hesitated but ended up hitting it. Then a couple feet of fun slab before interesting but decently easy face climbing. Lucia took on first crux, I struggled to give slack, until use carabiner in the nose to disengage brake rope. She crushed second attempt. Fun route!
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Sara. Favorite climb of the day and favorite gunks lead so far. Next time I would combine p1 and p2 but walkies were out of batteries, so we pitched it out to maintain communication. Heart got pumping a bit on the traverse as I struggled to find gear to protect the follow but a .4 then a .3 fit well. P3 is so much fun. Doing this in a triple would be enjoyable and would make the rappel faster. Sara loved it and got a bit higher in the traverse probably because I was keeping her to tight and it was forcing that direction. She should try it again keeping feet low. Would love to this next time with beginners. Also saw a plane flying below us which was so cool. Great end to the day.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > e. The Mac Wall (Something Interesting)

Notes: With Sara. Fun climb as always and a fast rappel. Chimney and step out were fun and almost trivial with a little crack technique. Great route for beginners and fun moves. Felt easy today.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: With Sara. Her first multipitch, trad, and gunks climb! She absolutely crushed it and was super confident. It was a great time and went really smoothly. Built an anchor on top of P1 which felt like a better and more controlled belay than going left to the tree and belaying from there. With a comfortable follower / next time with Sara, I would combine P1 and P2.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: Link led tied in middle of 80. Elizabeth and I followed. Perhaps best day/climb of the trip. Absolutely amazing. P1 starts stiff but HJ solves it. Chimney was cool I stayed on outside because it was tight. Works for a follow but would be a problem for a lead. Tunnel pitch was so fun, never climbed anything like it. Simuled gully because 40m rope was a bit short. It was easy climbing for followers and leader at that point so no big deal. Met trash dogs on route. Started late, ~7:30a and in parking lot by 1p. Linked used up to a 4
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (06) White Rock Spring > Angel Food Area > Angel Food Wall

Notes: Susan Led Mimi and I up P1 and we turned around. Absolutely stunning climb, Susan crushed. Problem is most people do a 30m run out on the slab to put a first piece of gear in the roof crack. We got some help from a party of Canadian simul climbers so didn’t have to place it. I think it’s very doable but when I led it. After reaching the first flake on the slab, I would place pro there. Traverse to the crack place pro there and then down climber to remove the flake pro. We learned there is bolted anchors at each pitch and rappelling each pitch is possible. So next time let’s go for a new high point. Amazing lead on that p1 Susan!
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (12) Oak Creek Canyon > Solar Slab - Upper Tier

Notes: Swapped leads with Susan. P1 was a bit stiff and route finding was hard. Stayed close to the topo but ended about 10” short of anchors. Susan led the 4th class scramble which definitely felt 5th class. Accidentally missed anchors belaying on tree instead of anchors on the right wall. I led P3 which was easy but rope drag was significant. With double 60m ropes I was able to skip the hanging anchors and belay off small tree in the slot chimney. This saved time and was more comfortable. We got help placing a draw on the top of the 5.3 chimney and Susan lead the rest of the way to the terrace then built an anchor. It would be better to go right after the last chimney and used the bolted anchor. We were slow but super good experience and fun time. Mimi followed.
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (12) Oak Creek Canyon > Solar Slab - Lower Tier

Notes: Susan lead. I would lead. RH hand jam off the deck. Easy climbing and placements follow. Top anchor was a bit strange. Looped low but large rock protrusion. Backed up with cams.
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (01) Calico Basin > Kraft Mountain Area > Yin and Yang Cliff

Notes: Link led with 2,3 for anchor; 5,6,7 for climbing. Very whimsical knee bar’ed the hole way up. Maybe with a little use for the other face. Susan belayed
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (01) Calico Basin > Kraft Mountain Area > Yin and Yang Cliff

Notes: Followed Tom, climbed behind jack and Kelsey. Great climb, P3/P4 is really beautiful, 45 min approach. Stiff move on P1 but can be well protected with two large cams (4). It’s fine just a bit awkward. Unroped for scramble to P2. Again stiff move off the second ledge in P2. Just burly, I threw a knee. Belay from top tree if possible makes P3 set up faster. P3 at roof section. Stay low on the traverse left and it’s way easier. Focus on good feet over good hands. P4 we didn’t go down but instead traverse right on handrails then straight up black slab. P4 was really cool.  Double rope rappels.
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (10) Pine Creek Canyon > Mescalito > Southeast Buttress

Notes: Climbed with 70m on back and hauled pack. Set up TR on main event and this for Jess, Jake, and Em. Fallen leaves made top fell a little sketchy so I used a tree anchor and a clove hitch to back it  up. Bolts were a bit hard to find with leaves.
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > s. Lower Stover

Notes: TR with 60 lb pack. Set up a couple top ropes for Jessie, Jake, and Em. They liked this area alot, the corner was great for them and the flat ground and the base was good for them to run around. Remember cordellete to extend anchor to the right next time.
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > s. Lower Stover

Notes: Best rep yet on it, climbed with Link, Holly, Seb, Matteo, Lucia, Sarah, and Paula. Climbed twice, one to set up and once to clean.
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > h. Open Face

Notes: Trad practice and setup for friends
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > b. Practice Face

Notes: Easy climbing up until, roof move. Fell on roof pull. No good, need better roof technique and strength. Missed side pull in the roof which needs to be a LH then right hand out then feet up and then find jugs and then... cut feet? Need to go right of tree. Susan worked real hard and crush it but may have injured her shoulder.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > h. The Arrow Wall - CCK

Notes: Susan led to celebrate her FPO. She crushed. I would definitely lead P1, traverse seems potentially sketchy if rope drag isn't well managed but super fun. Definitely a real move about midway up P1. P2 would go but still a pumpy for my fitness. Place #4, before roof. Maybe first placement after on side pull or first rail? But don't forget about that RH side pull and blind foot to clear the roof. P1 Anchor Sling boulder and backup, P2 tree anchor.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > i. High E

Notes: With Link and Susan. Crazy and unexpected climb. Chimney on p2 was tight exit for me but it went. Really fun but gotta be a dry day. Also maybe chalk bag on the side.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > h. The Arrow Wall - CCK

Notes: W/ Link and Susan. Link used every single piece and every nut possible while linking P1 and p2. Lead to some hilarious antics and creative placements. I was dying. Ran into Dan and Leslie from RV working out the dangler. Would definitely lead later but in three pitch. End of P2 had crux but would be fine if just confident while on lead. easily protectable.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > e. The Mac Wall (Something Interesting)

Notes: With Emmie, Addie, Jessie, and Susan.
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > h. Open Face

Notes: Set up TR for Emmie’s first climb on the 5.3! With Addie, Jessie, and Susan.
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > b. Practice Face

Notes: First multi pitch sport with Brandon. He led and crushed. I lowered him after first lead because wasn’t sure I wanted to climb. Then I followed his gear and top belayed him back up to ledge. Second pitch took some figuring out. Rappelled with 70m
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > i. Orangutan Buttress

Notes: W/ Brandon. Took at second to last bolt. Really hot day just couldn’t keep my hands dry. Really fun though
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > h. Open Face

Notes: W/ Brandon. Just to get trad reps
Location: Pennsylvania > Southeastern Lowlands > Ralph Stover State Park (High Rocks) > b. Practice Face

Notes: Link Led, w/ Brandon. Love this climb; we did variation 2 where you completely avoid froghead. Really fun but a bit hard. Brandon fell trying to crimp like crazy. I found really cool but still challenging beta. After the big pillar, theres a okay RF/RH and the crimps begin. I LH jammed and matched with LF then reached for big LH sidepull which it alot easier. Corners always great. Would lead because I love dihedral but traverse is scary
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > c. Frog's Head - the Arch

Notes: Link led and brandon crushed but i got shot down at the crux. Tried to mono it and should have tried some more fingers or a jam. Was falling about 15" restarting because link did it in one pitch. Would try again. lead looks scary
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > c. Frog's Head - the Arch

Notes: Lead two ropes. Link and Brandon; his first, my first time dealing with two ropes. With one rope I could see pitching it into 1 but one is comfortable with two tree anchors. Really fun but don't hesitate on in the crack just get in theres a right hand jug inside which allows you to grab top
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: Finally sent moonlit (buttress). Led first pitch, used a lot of gear. Felt like first proper gunks lead given it was from bottom to the GT ledge. Second pitch was so sick. Up into the roof and then step out and around the arete. Super fun but lead would be spicyyy for a 5.6. Link led second pitch. Susan led first pitch through my gear. Got good feedback on pro.  So stoked. Rappel was not possible in one with two 60m ropes would be possible with two 70s
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > h. The Arrow Wall - CCK

Notes: Link led after sleepwalkin p1. God damn this was really dope. About 10 ft up the face there is two stacked chalked up hands and nothing for a couple feet. Make sure you get your LH on that top hold at which point you can make a big move for the jug which is at the top of the bulge. It’s a good jug and far. I actually lost feet. Took me awhile to get the beta here. Following is a left hand side pull or crimp option and the stand up into the roof to reach for a nice jug on the next bulge. Maybe 2 foot from the roof. Took here because it’s out of sight and looks like a sloper from below. Super fun climb but very beta intense. Ty Susan for Beta
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > i. High E

Notes: Climbed with link and Susan. So sickkkkkkk. Worth the wait. Could not be better holds, great spots for placements. Link linked p2 and P3 but complain about rope drag at top. This is a goal lead but would recommend pitching it out and taking it slow, don’t do it on a busy weekend. The last roof is fine just rest and go for it. There are jugs in reach. Sketchiest part was very last mantle. Probably better beta available. We tied a 60m and 70m together for the rap to get all the way to the ground. My favorite rappel so far at the gunks

Notes: Link Led, Followed w/ Holly. Still my favorite climb so far at the gunks. P1 standard but one real move on shield. P2 we switched it up, instead of doing traditionally method of going up updraft corner, link lead first small (wet) corner about 15 ft to right, easy moves up to small ledge, shimmy to handholds and some burly moves up. Unfortunately had to take because couldn't get cam out after making move. Got it following go by unclipping it really low after move. Didn't link 2-3 to get some good photos. Such a great pitch, stay low as long as possible and step out over exposure after piton, until you hit first vertical crack, hard to remove cam meant I was stuck here until link rapped down to get it from above haha. Then to main vertical crack, use small LF on face, LH hand jam, RH on flake, to get good RF on flake. stand up and grab jug, only make one move on top thin rail then reach high and get jugs, traverse right and finish. Amazing Climb
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > h. The Arrow Wall - CCK

Notes: Link Led, Followed w/ Holly. Really fun easy climbing. Had some legit move but felts cruiser and enjoyable.

Notes: Link Led, Followed w/ Holly. Ran P1-2 together and the rope drag was immense on Link would not recommend. Start at ramp at tree, I felt unsure because link couldn't pull slack due to so much drag. I karate kicked tree to stabilize. Roof was fine but took a long time finding feet hands which allowed span to jug. 10' below p1 belay ledge is where I got in trouble. Hard to tell if chalked up thin vertical crack or right corner then traverse was correct method. Both are doable, linked took right but holly and I struggled on crack, might have been enduro, link says corner was all jugs. If doing thin crack, side pulls on left work your way up with RH on crack then large dynamic move to jug rail. Link said corner to jug rail traverse was easier. Start of P2, was fun long moves between jugs. Rest of it was easy but beautiful arete climbing of the nose of high E buttress. Fun but need to figure out end of P1. Next time stick to corner traverse!
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > i. High E

Notes: Left at 10p returned at 3:30a from star gazing with Oak/Annie. Link/Jack led. Tom Kels Eric follow. New moon, pitch black, many stars but couldn’t see much of climb. Fun experience but preference on full moon. P1, easy climbing up to flaring chimney aided bolt ladder,  P2 mud chimney a bit harder. P3 short/aided bolt ladder. P4 craziness. Link led (forgot bolts and had to come back). Was run out and quite scary in dark due to visibility. After link sent, set up dual belay for other 4 climbers. Classic follow, then a tag line to keep the climber tight and on the platform for the descent. There was no pro on the walk over / diving board. Super fun, highly recommend. Rapped with dual 60s to p1 ledge then 70m to ground

Notes:
Link led, what a hero. Drove up from montichello after two days at IC. Got started around 9:30-10a. Approach was difficult but  type II fun. I was slow, need to improve but enjoyed it. Link/Jack scrambled boulders on ground and lowered a rope for Tom/Kels/I to go up, wasn't hard but rope was nice. P1 started with hard problem but stemming left side allowed me to send this section. Rest of pitch 1 was good hand jams
with awkward body position. I extremely tired but pushed through the cruxs with lots of rests on cams. Crux with wobbling chockstone stuck in crack system was crazy! P2 had OW boulder problem which I found perfect beta, knee into first foothold and drop foot against right side chimney for locked knee bar, work hands and LF without body weight then reach high. This was heady part for link, chimney and cracks very polished. P2/3 after OW was fun easy/moderate chimneys exit to the left then step over. 15 feet of face climbing where we meet up with our friends on the other side of the tower. Rapped off north side with a 70m (heady to get over edge), skipped first anchors to barely make it two second, then short rap to third, then to ground-ish. Down climb was bit sketch but okay, had some makeshift raps. walk out was lovely in nice drizzle. Amazing lead by Link and Jack. Happy with my effort to push through. great day
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Castle Valley > Castleton Tower

Route: Supercrack of the Desert (aka Luxury Liner)
Notes: Followed but struggled with boulder problem off the deck. Link led with 4x3s and 3x4s. Was so close to getting first crux but couldn't find beta after first go. Finally got it with LF/RF jam, LH high far back slopy undercling and RH slide up into finger jam. Pull up to fridge. Was so burnt from 7-8 attempts until i got lower crux I barely got much distance or effort into the supercrack. Although I could feel my lack of crack technique, excited to hopefully try again some day

Link placed big cames 4s and a 5

Notes: Jack led. Absolutely amazing climb. First pitch was easy but fun climbing. Couple little pulls but with boomer hands and feet. Linked 2nd and 3rd. 2nd was also chill dihedral climbing. 3rd was money pitch. Traverse right on small hands and smaller wider feet. Work your way to a crack. Stemming wide helped. Decide between layback and it’s not feet or bomber hand jam with left on left. I took the left hand jam swung to high jug. Walk crimp rail to wine really good hands. Finish up and rap to the right. Top 3 gunks climb so far.

Notes: 1st pitch is chill small hands and delicate feet. Really fun though. 2nd pitch is jug fest. One burly move off the deck then pretty much cruise to the top. Rapped off with fixed 70m. Jack lead. Link was leading bonnies with Megan and John with a ruptured pulley

Notes: Jake lead. Classic climb, had good time but hot day and my butt kicked on first big roof. Work hands on jug rail get high LH on big flake. Get high left foot in crack and turn. Get RH statically. Get left foot into crack and work LH into right crack layback match. Stand up and finish. Really loved 2nd pitch. Exposed but really picturesque. Stay low on traverse and work the arete to the top. Classic. Try again for n the fall and send
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > i. High E

Notes: Tom’s first alpine lead, he crushed. Approach put us was to the right. Long scramble through scree then hike left to base, short scramble up to start of climb. Starts with hand crack, important LF on left, follow up to easy belay. P2 hard to see but right hand crack is layback “unlikely looking” but very solid lay back. Standing on flake is thin but great. P3 up the Vgroove past some pitons move out left in not big ol LF. Superior LF slide beta haha. P4 pipe pitch, exposed but beautiful climbing breath and find jugs. After mantling pipe  find high LH, take your time, there’s a big jug but it’s tall beta for sure. P5 slab then dihedral then slab but kinda hanging belay with three pitons. Spent a little time route finding. Tom ending up on 5.8 but down climbed because piton lead that way. P6 Make sure to go out left from there little bit of 5.7 then scramble to top. Hike back to find bike trail. Was covered with snow but there was fresh steps from previous group. Tom crushed it. I would lead in future after getting a bit stronger and experienced. Would return.  Link and Jack simuled behind and did what we did in 5 hours in an hour.
Location: New Hampshire > *Cannon Cliff > 1. Whitney-Gilman Area

Notes: Link lead, jack lead, Tom and I followed. Approach up scree field. Got my ass kicked in the cracks and cave but what a classic. P1 hand crack was amazing, actually felt good but suffered at fingers section. Ankles hurting by the end just get better at the hands and work faster. Pain is a bit unavoidable. Finger cracks section was hardest, thumbs down and cam. P2 triangle roof, lay back hard, struggled from wet feet popping then get high hand jam. P3 really fun face climbing and short hand cracks. Then the span between a jug and another flake. Really fun, foot popped when let go of left but kept the right hand on. P4 FoF what a sketchy led this would be, chimney as much as you can and then I inches dyno’d for the top jug at the climbers left of the flake. V1 slab after the flake was so sketch on lead link dyno’d it. P5 kicked my ass. Cave crack was wet but just pull hard get up to good LF. Get top jug rail in cave then get RF in cave on left and LF higher. Reach for top corner jug on outside with RH match with LH. Get RF out in face and then get hand jam up. Great two crack system with pinch after. Top of this pitch had really wet crack slab. SKETCH. I lowered rope and put jack on belay for it. P6/7 scramble. Super easy decent keep climbers right close to the cliff find helipad then old man’s face and follow concert slide to descent trial
Location: New Hampshire > *Cannon Cliff > 4. Moby Grape Area

Notes: Followed Tom 3rd lead. What a great climb. He struggled on the lead but powered through. It is definitely a step up and requires real climbing. I sent it easily but would be nervous to lead. 1st roof get high feet and grab jug above w/ LH. 2nd roof, tall beta jugs, there was a LH which was like a monkey bar find it breath, get high feet, and pull on jugs. 2nd pitch, we went into the Right corner (2nd pitch of classic) and it was amazing, highly highly recommend over normal 2nd pitch. rapped down twiced used 70 m.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: As someone that got into climbing due to a love of falling, this route (and maybe eldo in general) isn’t for me. I don’t love climbing when I shouldn’t fall, and that is what this route is about. P1 was fun and burly. For P3, followed bolts up the 11 var. P4 is actually protected well enough with a 0.2 alien. But then the next good hold is a dinner plate that will not survive another decade before being choss. I don’t think this route should be a classic and I think this route losses a hold every couple years.

Notes:
Brought an 80 m rope, didn’t need it. 70 m would’ve been fine.
Didn’t bring anything larger than a #3, if you trad climb 5.10 there’s no need.
Started up at 6 AM, took long relaxing breaks at every bolt station and topped out at 10:30a.
Rapelling took one hour.
The jump traverse is sick, I recommend doing the jump. It feels competition style, but easy 
My favorite pitch was the bowling alley(the approach)
Group in front of us also had a van and were good company. the leader had a recovering ankle.

Notes: lead with kn and tu- sprinkled rain on and off a couple times, wind dried it very quickly. p1 had squeeze and some stemming. p2 had a wide slick crack- took a #3 but was mostly #4. #5 may work, i also jammed a 6 in there. crack was very polished, could not get good jams but the kayback went ok. p3 had a short cruxy corner with the tat pro and then the scariest part of the climb was the loose blocks in the chimney before the crux. crux was very fun and protected by bolts then tat, fun and grunty dive into squeeze chimney. p4 took the face- very easy 5.7 and the chimney looked hard to protect. met up with lp and eb at the top, super classic summit and tower. kn had a grunt getting into the squeeze on p3 and a minor panic attack. tu could not fit in the original way and had to climb higher. climbed p4 together with other group.

Notes: Lead pitches 1,2.  Very fun. Didn't actually place that many nuts on P1. Small gear is useful. Link lead P3, probably the spookiest. The traverse is quite hollow, wouldn't want to place anything there. Might want the roller biner there. Eric led P4, a bit scarcer gear but good climbing. Link lead P5, super chill until the finger crack which was small and slippery. Lots of good 0-0.2 on the right. Crux is at the big sloper that looks like a jug. There is a jam in the back left of that block. Did a single rap to P4 anchor then double rap to P2 then double 70 rap to ground. Lots of potential to get rope stuck. 5hr 40 mins car to car.

Notes: Started working on it today. Third time here, first time just did the tens on the right, second time was too cold and snowy. Today also hiked in the snow and ice to get here but it’s so warm on this wall. Link is projecting the 13c eastern promises, and I’m projecting this one for the winter. They might both be over our heads, many say this is a 13a since holds keep breaking off and it’s sandbagged to start. But… the hard part turned out to be a slab! Anyway the first section leads up to a roof. Moves are doable but physical and then getting over the roof and pulling up on a crimp are all very exhausting for me. After that I love this climb. Very interesting, slabby and vertical moves. A good foot, thinking it might be a pistol squat on the right leg but I can’t really do that and my knees have been hurting a little lately. So next time I want to do the beginning better and find some ideas for that crux slab part. There are some good possibilities a little to the left. But hard since the right foot is way out. I’m excited about this climb!! Even if I don’t lead it cleanly would be awesome to make some progress on this while we’re living in Boulder. Will climb it someday for sure :)
Location: Colorado > Boulder > Boulder Canyon > Lower Dream Canyon > Berlin Wall

Notes: Lead with Eric and Link, so much fun. It was our last day in Red Rocks after several days of climbing over Thanksgiving. We were all a little tired, but woke up early, said bye to Link’s parents after having breakfast with them in their trailer. And then headed to the trail. Eric and I went ahead and tried to figure out what Link meant by “turn right after 500 yards”. Got a little nervous, tried calling Link, he finally showed up. Hike was sunny and beautiful, got to the base pretty fast. Started climbing, first part was a little tricky because I was using slopers instead of stemming. Eric did it very well. Then we ran into the trash dogs, maybe 2-3 pitches in. They tried passing us but changed their minds, was a little chaotic. But then we continued on ahead. My index finger was split and would’ve started bleeding so I was trying to climb with the other fingers. Next couple pitches were fun, lots of chimneys but you could avoid them, lots of options. Amazing cave after the 4th pitch. Link aka cave yeti led it and then Eric and I had a ton of fun going through it. One of the trash dogs (not litter kitten but the other one whose name I don’t remember was there with us). Then Link was leading to the end but ran out of rope, told us to just start climbing together. Right after we had talked about this scenario the night before at dinner and how it’s not super safe. But anyway it was easy climbing and we got to the top! Ended too fast. Hiked back down and then had beers and chatted with our friends by the van.
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (06) White Rock Spring > Angel Food Area > Angel Food Wall

Notes: Super hard, my first 13 attempt. Mainly came to this wall to see Shawn do some hard stuff since he took a rest day yesterday and seemed excited for this. Two other guys were there climbing some 12s next to us. I was having some beers with Link and hanging out in the sun, Shawn did great, figured out the beta after I told him what they did in a YouTube video. Then Link tried it. And then I tried haha, wasn’t planning to but it was cool to touch a 13 for the first time! Some really tough moves on it but seems doable once you have a good plan. Ripped my index finger open on this one and it was bleeding a lot the next few days. Great day overall, went on a drive though the loop road after this!
Location: Nevada > Southern Nevada > Red Rocks > (03) First Pullout (Calico I) > Tsunami Wall

Notes:
Link led this, took him about 40 minutes. The beginning looked super scary to lead, but was very fun when top roping. There was a lot of snow on the ground and my fingers were very cold by the end (the rope was wet). He did great. Then we did jumping jacks and warmed up, and I top roped it. It went well, I enjoyed the slab by sections and there were 4ish? roofs. They weren’t as hard as I expected! (Normally I struggle with roofs). It was a super fun climb and the view at the top was beautiful. We did this climb in the evening and I spent a while at the top looking at the scenery and feeling happy. :)
Also the area adjacent to this (directly to the right when facing the wall) was blocked off for peregrine falcons, while Link was climbing a few of them circled overhead.

Notes: The route almost defeated me on p2 crack. But I finally got through it and was rewarded with the super exhilarating walk along the sky. Literally no-one else on the mountain that day, definitely hit the jackpot w that. The descent scared me but then through the woods felt like a dream.

New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > c. Frog's Head - the Arch

Notes: First slab outside. Adam helped me with technique as I was on the wall. Learning to trust my feet as I smear. It was very interesting to think through how to move up the wall with basically no feet, especially at the crux. I think I only had to take/fell at the crux but did so many times. Learning new styles is cool.
Location: West Virginia > The New River Gorge Region > New River Gorge Proper > Endless Wall > E) Kaymoor Slabs

Route: With a Little Help from My Friends
Notes: First 10 climb but maybe won’t fully claim it as that since I had “a little help from my friend”. Kai gave me a generous belay at both cruxes…especially the first one after I tried it many times. I got the move down but couldn’t stand up on my left foot on the hand match without pushing myself off the wall. Time to practice those pistol squats. Proud of myself. Slab is fun…on top rope! Could have finished off the climb strong but Kai lifted me w/o asking. I had a fun time on this one.
Location: West Virginia > The New River Gorge Region > New River Gorge Proper > Endless Wall > E) Kaymoor Slabs

Notes: First crack section. Weirdly and surprisingly loved it. I could see if I was climbing a longer crack how I would get into a really nice meditative groove with foot and hand jams. Off-width section was fun but still freaks me out. Hard! Did my first foot and hand jams and felt good doing it. Wore Adam’s crack gloves and tried to really stick my arm in the crack. Hands were a little small for some sections of it. Last big move was hard for me but I got it and felt good. More new styles and technique ! Yeeehaw
Location: West Virginia > The New River Gorge Region > New River Gorge Proper > Endless Wall > E) Kaymoor Slabs

Notes: First 5.9 outside, had to take a ton and Kai aid belayed me up but I got it!

Notes: Got halfway up before it got too dark. Prob could have got to the top with a lot of help from Kai. Adam gave me super good technique help
Location: West Virginia > The New River Gorge Region > Summersville (Gauley River) Area > Summersville Lake (main) > The Long Wall

Notes:
First climb with Emily!!!
Super wet and slimy right at the crux. Took a nice lil spinning whip from the rope pulling me around the corner after cleaning a piece. Slightly spicy first two pitches for me, felt like a fun challenge and showed me that I was getting stronger. 

Headlamp died as I was starting the last pitch, had to do it with phone flashlight in shirt. Pitch black. Not fun. Thankfully it was super short. Made it to the top fine but then had to do the small down climb to the rap station in the pitch black too. Oof. Taylor at the top helped.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > f. The Guides' Wall (Madame G's)

Notes: Nice climb although it wasn’t too exciting for me. I felt a bit off on the first pitch but then got my stride. Felt pretty easy and straightforward, not has fun as I thought it would be.

Notes: Super fun climb. Challenging start for me. Felt quick and strong following Kai.

Route: A Long Walk For Man, A Short Climb For Mankind
Notes: Name is very accurate. Fun, easy climbing but the approach is a bit too long to make it worth it. Had friends climbing on Sleepy Hollow so it was fine. But this did feel like it shouldn’t even be considered on that wall. A good ways past this wall with the trail completely blown out.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > l. Sleepy Hollow

Notes: Combined the first two pitches to meet friends on the ledge overlooking the dangler. Got to watch Adam and Joseph send it which was sweet. Good fun and easy climbing. I’ll finish the climb next time, probably stopping again at the ledge to belay Kai on the Dangler.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > e. The Mac Wall (Something Interesting)

Notes: Climbed with headlamps in the evening as the sky got dark. Found second mini roof to be much harder than first. Struggled quite a bit. Kai was close behind me as we were double top-roping (?) which helped when I was pumped out.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > b. Jackie and friends

Notes: First chimney. Got stuck in there for a good 20 mins not knowing the right wiggle squiggle technique. Dropped my Chaco. Bug got it for me. Full moonrise as we topped out. Simul-rapped down.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > h. The Arrow Wall - CCK

Notes: My first 5.8 in the gunks ! Got stuck for a bit at the crux (small roof) but with some good beta from friends I got myself up. A lean back up to two finger holds under the roof got me over. Fun the rest of the way up.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > l. Sleepy Hollow

Notes: Fun route. Tricky start to the second pitch. Honestly, I weirdly can’t remember this climb at all even though I did it two days ago. Does that say something about it?
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > i. High E

Notes: Favorite climb so far that I’ve done in the gunks ! Loved the little traverse and exposure. Super fun and good moderate (easy) climbing. Overall great time and would do again. I think we combined a pitch or two cause I don’t remember it being 4.
Location: New York > The Gunks > The Trapps > h. The Arrow Wall - CCK

Notes: First multi-pitch, first follow, and first time climbing outside in 5+ years. Had a freak out moment in the middle and sat in the second pitch hanging belay for an hour. Finished strong !
